WEBVTT

00:06.089 --> 00:08.842
<i>[intense music]</i>

00:08.842 --> 00:10.886
<i>- Tonight,</i>
<i>"Forged In Fire" celebrates</i>

00:10.886 --> 00:12.930
<i>U. S. military history</i>

00:12.930 --> 00:15.224
<i>and the men and women</i>
<i>who lived it.</i>

00:15.224 --> 00:17.476
<i>Four bladesmiths,</i>
<i>all veterans</i>

00:17.476 --> 00:18.936
<i>of the United States</i>
<i>Armed Forces,</i>

00:18.936 --> 00:20.437
<i>bring their talent</i>
<i>and training</i>

00:20.437 --> 00:22.439
<i>to serve</i>
<i>in a competitive tribute.</i>

00:22.439 --> 00:25.067
- We ain't got time
to mess around, baby!

00:25.067 --> 00:28.487
<i>- Which veteran's guts</i>
<i>will propel them to glory...</i>

00:28.487 --> 00:30.906
- Now we're rockin' it.

00:30.906 --> 00:33.033
<i>- ...and earn them the title</i>
<i>of "Forged in Fire" Champion?</i>

00:33.033 --> 00:34.743
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:34.743 --> 00:37.412
<i>[intense music]</i>

00:40.082 --> 00:44.086
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:44.086 --> 00:45.796
- My name's Jon Nagel.

00:45.796 --> 00:47.673
I've been in the Army Reserves
for 14 years.

00:47.673 --> 00:49.841
<i>My current job</i>
<i>is a Battalion S3</i>

00:49.841 --> 00:51.927
<i>Operations Officer.</i>

00:51.927 --> 00:55.305
That basically entails anything
that has to do with, uh...

00:55.305 --> 00:57.140
It's kind of hard
to explain in civilian terms,

00:57.140 --> 00:59.476
to be honest with you.

00:59.476 --> 01:02.771
- My name is Mike Miller,
my age is 53, today!

01:02.771 --> 01:05.148
<i>I was in the Marine Corps</i>
<i>in the early '80s.</i>

01:05.148 --> 01:07.568
Got to go a few places,
see a few things, you know.

01:07.568 --> 01:09.111
Some things I'd rather
not have seen.

01:10.821 --> 01:12.823
<i>- My name is Jim McGuinn.</i>

01:12.823 --> 01:15.492
I served in the Army
during the Vietnam conflict,

01:15.492 --> 01:17.411
<i>where I was an armored scout.</i>

01:17.411 --> 01:19.580
Basically a-a target.

01:19.580 --> 01:22.666
<i>As a reward, they gave me</i>
<i>two Purple Hearts</i>

01:22.666 --> 01:24.376
for the two times
that I was shot.

01:24.376 --> 01:26.670
We were very good at our job.

01:26.670 --> 01:29.423
- My name is Perry Johnson,
and I served

01:29.423 --> 01:30.757
in the United States Army,

01:30.757 --> 01:32.259
the only branch there is.

01:32.259 --> 01:34.011
Everything else is just a twig.

01:34.011 --> 01:35.596
<i>I was a combat medic,</i>

01:35.596 --> 01:37.472
<i>and now I work</i>
<i>with other vets,</i>

01:37.472 --> 01:38.849
<i>helping them</i>
<i>through addiction</i>

01:38.849 --> 01:41.476
and also through trauma.

01:41.476 --> 01:44.146
- Bladesmiths,
welcome to the Forge.

01:44.146 --> 01:45.939
You're here
for three timed rounds

01:45.939 --> 01:47.607
of edged-weapon-making
competition,

01:47.607 --> 01:50.110
designed to test every aspect
of your skills,

01:50.110 --> 01:51.445
in the hopes
of becoming the next

01:51.445 --> 01:52.904
"Forged in Fire" Champion

01:52.904 --> 01:55.157
and winning a check
for $10,000.

01:55.157 --> 01:57.534
Behind me are the guys
who make that decision,

01:57.534 --> 01:59.870
so let's meet them now.

01:59.870 --> 02:03.081
Up first,
ABS Master smith J. Neilson.

02:03.081 --> 02:05.167
<i>Historic weapons</i>
<i>re-creation specialist</i>

02:05.167 --> 02:06.835
<i>David Baker.</i>

02:06.835 --> 02:08.628
<i>Edged weapons specialist</i>
<i>Doug Marcaida.</i>

02:08.628 --> 02:10.422
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:10.422 --> 02:12.341
Anybody want to take a guess
at what this is?

02:12.341 --> 02:14.801
<i>[sinister music]</i>

02:14.801 --> 02:16.678
- It's a hedgehog.

02:16.678 --> 02:19.431
- That's correct,
that is a Czech hedgehog.

02:19.431 --> 02:23.602
A static anti-tank obstacle,
specifically designed

02:23.602 --> 02:26.396
to prevent light-to-medium
weight tanks and vehicles

02:26.396 --> 02:28.899
from breaching the line
of defense.

02:28.899 --> 02:31.151
<i>74 years ago,</i>
<i>almost to the day,</i>

02:31.151 --> 02:32.819
<i>with the eyes of the world</i>
<i>upon them,</i>

02:32.819 --> 02:35.113
<i>America's bravest,</i>
<i>and her Allies,</i>

02:35.113 --> 02:37.032
<i>stormed the beaches</i>
<i>of Normandy</i>

02:37.032 --> 02:40.369
<i>to free France</i>
<i>from Nazi occupation.</i>

02:40.369 --> 02:43.330
Today, you will be
forging your blades

02:43.330 --> 02:45.957
with steel harvested
from this hedgehog,

02:45.957 --> 02:49.628
and combining it
with the 10-95 on your anvils

02:49.628 --> 02:51.505
to form your blades.

02:51.505 --> 02:54.216
<i>- We're doing D-Day,</i>
<i>we are doing Normandy,</i>

02:54.216 --> 02:56.093
we're doing the beach!

02:56.093 --> 02:57.636
Awesome!

02:57.636 --> 02:59.805
- Now, bladesmiths,
forging a blade

02:59.805 --> 03:02.808
in your signature style
is quite an accomplishment.

03:02.808 --> 03:04.434
But since you're all vets,

03:04.434 --> 03:06.103
today we're giving you
a chance to put your own

03:06.103 --> 03:08.230
unique spin on a familiar tool:

03:08.230 --> 03:10.148
<i>the combat knife.</i>

03:10.148 --> 03:12.109
<i>That includes weapons</i>
<i>as diverse</i>

03:12.109 --> 03:14.319
<i>as the Marine Corps'</i>
<i>hefty and versatile KA-BAR,</i>

03:14.319 --> 03:16.196
<i>and the Special Forces'</i>
<i>lethal V-42</i>

03:16.196 --> 03:17.989
<i>double-edged stiletto.</i>

03:17.989 --> 03:20.659
<i>- The combat knife</i>
<i>is a multi-purpose tool</i>

03:20.659 --> 03:22.369
that can be used
for everything

03:22.369 --> 03:23.995
from opening
a can of C-rations,

03:23.995 --> 03:27.249
to defending your life.

03:27.249 --> 03:28.875
- Keep in mind
that in the second round,

03:28.875 --> 03:30.585
you'll be attaching handles
to those blades.

03:30.585 --> 03:33.255
Turning them into
fully-functional combat knives

03:33.255 --> 03:35.424
that will be tested
for strength and durability

03:35.424 --> 03:38.593
in an ammo can
chop-and-stab test.

03:38.593 --> 03:40.554
And for edge retention,

03:40.554 --> 03:43.557
in a resupply bundle slice.

03:43.557 --> 03:46.476
You will have three hours
to forge your blades.

03:46.476 --> 03:50.021
Good luck.
Your three hours starts... now.

03:50.021 --> 03:53.066
<i>♪ ♪</i>

03:53.066 --> 03:54.901
<i>- So, we've got</i>
<i>our four veterans</i>

03:54.901 --> 03:58.280
scurrying about the forge,
looking to harvest some steel.

03:58.280 --> 04:01.032
Do you expect that these guys
are gonna work in teams, Doug?

04:01.032 --> 04:02.451
- Absolutely.
Even though this is

04:02.451 --> 04:04.453
an individual competition,

04:04.453 --> 04:07.414
in the military,
we work as a team.

04:07.414 --> 04:09.249
- Here, help me out, man.
- They're gonna yell

04:09.249 --> 04:10.459
if I don't have
safety glasses on.

04:10.459 --> 04:12.127
- Oh, here, here.

04:12.127 --> 04:13.962
Being in the military
is absolutely a brotherhood.

04:13.962 --> 04:16.047
<i>So when I found out that Wil</i>
<i>is also a veteran,</i>

04:16.047 --> 04:18.550
I knew that we were all
gonna speak the same language.

04:18.550 --> 04:20.760
- You want handle material
for your billet and stuff?

04:20.760 --> 04:22.471
- Yes, please.
- Three of us are Army.

04:22.471 --> 04:25.140
The other gentleman, Mike,
is a Marine Corps veteran.

04:25.140 --> 04:26.808
We're all gonna pull
for each other,

04:26.808 --> 04:30.103
but if I lose to a Marine,
I'll never forgive myself.

04:30.103 --> 04:31.480
[laughs]

04:31.480 --> 04:34.149
- Now, J, talk to me
a little bit about

04:34.149 --> 04:36.526
how much steel
they're gonna need

04:36.526 --> 04:39.488
off of this hedgehog.
- At least one strip of that.

04:39.488 --> 04:42.032
<i>You stretch that out,</i>
<i>and then they have</i>

04:42.032 --> 04:44.618
to forge that 1095 down, too,
to be able to make their stack

04:44.618 --> 04:46.912
for the San Mai.
- So you expect to see

04:46.912 --> 04:49.456
four San Mai constructions
out here.

04:49.456 --> 04:52.250
- Yeah, that would be
the way to go.

04:52.250 --> 04:54.503
- I love the idea
of doing a combat knife.

04:54.503 --> 04:56.713
Wow, this [bleep] is thick.

04:56.713 --> 04:58.715
- Watch your feet
when that bad boy drops.

04:58.715 --> 05:01.259
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:01.259 --> 05:02.469
- You watch yours!
- Gotta listen

05:02.469 --> 05:04.513
to my own advice!

05:04.513 --> 05:06.515
<i>- Some of the first thoughts</i>
<i>that came to my mind</i>

05:06.515 --> 05:07.682
when I saw it was,
"How are we going

05:07.682 --> 05:09.142
"to cut it off of there?"

05:09.142 --> 05:10.393
Let's see...
Shoot that way,

05:10.393 --> 05:12.395
slag's gonna go that way.

05:12.395 --> 05:15.357
My plan is
to cut the mild steel

05:15.357 --> 05:17.651
<i>into two pieces,</i>
<i>sandwich them</i>

05:17.651 --> 05:20.487
<i>over the knife steel,</i>
<i>and then pull</i>

05:20.487 --> 05:21.905
<i>the San Mai billet,</i>
<i>and draw it out</i>

05:21.905 --> 05:23.532
<i>into a knife shape.</i>

05:23.532 --> 05:26.117
- Get a hammer!
<i>- I doubt that I've got</i>

05:26.117 --> 05:28.161
<i>anything to teach</i>
<i>the other bladesmiths.</i>

05:28.161 --> 05:30.413
But I think my age
probably intimidates them

05:30.413 --> 05:32.415
a little bit
because, you know,

05:32.415 --> 05:34.835
<i>I've been making blades</i>
<i>since some of them were born.</i>

05:34.835 --> 05:37.796
<i>[intense music]</i>

05:37.796 --> 05:40.048
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:42.175 --> 05:43.885
- I have made combat knives

05:43.885 --> 05:45.720
<i>for guys who are deploying,</i>

05:45.720 --> 05:47.973
who have been deployed,
and for vets.

05:47.973 --> 05:50.183
<i>I make knives</i>
<i>that you could take</i>

05:50.183 --> 05:52.435
and pass to your kids.

05:52.435 --> 05:54.521
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:54.521 --> 05:55.772
<i>- The combat knife</i>
<i>I'm going to make</i>

05:55.772 --> 05:57.190
is a sharp, pointy thing.

05:57.190 --> 05:59.526
Because it comes down to it,
a combat knife

05:59.526 --> 06:01.653
is whatever you've got
in your hand

06:01.653 --> 06:03.697
when the situation arises.

06:03.697 --> 06:05.866
The most challenging part
is going to be

06:05.866 --> 06:07.534
to get the welds to stick.

06:07.534 --> 06:09.995
<i>Because I tend to hurry,</i>
<i>and, uh--</i>

06:09.995 --> 06:12.664
If you don't get it hot enough,
it's not gonna stick.

06:12.664 --> 06:15.667
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:15.667 --> 06:17.544
- I'm gonna go down there,
I'm gonna ask Jon

06:17.544 --> 06:20.547
how he plans on forge-welding
this stuff together.

06:20.547 --> 06:22.549
- What's up, Jon?
- How's it going, man?

06:22.549 --> 06:24.217
- So, combat knife.
What's the first thing

06:24.217 --> 06:26.136
that pops in your head?
- KA-BAR.

06:26.136 --> 06:27.637
- How you planning to forge
both the steels together?

06:27.637 --> 06:29.848
- I wanna draw out
the steel you guys gave us,

06:29.848 --> 06:31.516
into a workable billet.
- Okay.

06:31.516 --> 06:32.851
- Then I'll take
the other steel,

06:32.851 --> 06:35.186
draw it out,
wrap it around it,

06:35.186 --> 06:36.688
<i>forge weld it--</i>
<i>- So you're gonna do,</i>

06:36.688 --> 06:37.898
<i>like a taco technique.</i>
<i>- Exactly.</i>

06:37.898 --> 06:39.441
- All right,
you feel confident?

06:39.441 --> 06:42.193
- Absolutely.
- All right, good to know.

06:42.193 --> 06:45.071
<i>- J, is Perry working</i>
<i>that steel too cold?</i>

06:45.071 --> 06:47.115
<i>- Perry's working it</i>
<i>pretty cold, yeah.</i>

06:47.115 --> 06:49.242
Beating on cold steel,
you got a chance

06:49.242 --> 06:50.660
to put stress fractures.

06:50.660 --> 06:52.454
- My plan to combine
these pieces of steel

06:52.454 --> 06:54.873
is to take the piece
from the tank trap,

06:54.873 --> 06:57.083
fold it with the 1095
in the center,

06:57.083 --> 07:00.170
<i>and make a San Mai taco,</i>
<i>and forge weld it.</i>

07:00.170 --> 07:02.589
Now we're rockin' it!

07:02.589 --> 07:05.175
- Whoo-hoo-hoo-hoo!

07:05.175 --> 07:08.136
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:08.136 --> 07:10.096
- Mike,
you're our only Marine.

07:10.096 --> 07:11.431
- I know!
- So, uh,

07:11.431 --> 07:12.807
what do you think of
when you hear:

07:12.807 --> 07:14.976
"Fighting knife,"
or "combat knife"?

07:14.976 --> 07:16.770
- Marine Corps, KA-BAR.
- KA-BAR.

07:16.770 --> 07:18.021
- Exactly what I think.
- How do you plan

07:18.021 --> 07:19.648
on forge welding
your steel?

07:19.648 --> 07:21.232
- I'm gonna do a San Mai,

07:21.232 --> 07:22.942
one on either side.
- All right, brother.

07:22.942 --> 07:25.445
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:25.445 --> 07:27.280
- Time for you
to set that taco.

07:27.280 --> 07:30.909
- Ain't got time
to mess around, baby!

07:30.909 --> 07:32.827
What I want to accomplish
in this step

07:32.827 --> 07:35.789
<i>is to get a good marrying</i>
<i>of the high-carbon steel</i>

07:35.789 --> 07:37.207
<i>with the mild steel</i>

07:37.207 --> 07:39.376
so that I don't have any gaps.

07:39.376 --> 07:40.543
<i>But it's not</i>
<i>forge welding.</i>

07:40.543 --> 07:42.003
Sumbitch!

07:42.003 --> 07:43.963
- Taco's always
a little tricky,

07:43.963 --> 07:46.424
'cause you can always have
that seam on the back end,

07:46.424 --> 07:49.219
where that mild steel's
going over.

07:49.219 --> 07:51.554
I'd rather cut it
and stack it, personally.

07:51.554 --> 07:55.308
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:55.308 --> 07:57.477
<i>- Is it necessary</i>

07:57.477 --> 08:01.272
for Perry to be drawing
that 1095 steel out that far?

08:01.272 --> 08:03.358
- All he's doing
is making more surface area

08:03.358 --> 08:05.193
that he has to weld.

08:05.193 --> 08:06.611
<i>- I'm spending a lot of time</i>
<i>with Big Blue.</i>

08:06.611 --> 08:08.029
I think the excitement
is starting

08:08.029 --> 08:10.073
to really get to me.

08:10.073 --> 08:13.827
<i>My heart is really racing,</i>
<i>my hand is really hurting.</i>

08:13.827 --> 08:16.371
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:16.371 --> 08:18.373
- Damn it!
- Mike's billet looks rough.

08:18.373 --> 08:21.459
Not only is it duck-lipping,
but the lips are sliding.

08:21.459 --> 08:22.919
- Yeah, shifting.

08:22.919 --> 08:27.048
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:27.048 --> 08:29.092
- [bleep] me.

08:29.092 --> 08:32.846
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:32.846 --> 08:36.599
When I do Damascus,
I have a 50% failure rate,

08:36.599 --> 08:39.102
because forge welding
is not my staple.

08:39.102 --> 08:42.814
But I learned not
to chase turds

08:42.814 --> 08:44.983
by getting smacked
a whole bunch of times

08:44.983 --> 08:47.902
by the master bladesmith
I learned from.

08:47.902 --> 08:50.280
Screw it.
Rule 1: Abandon.

08:50.280 --> 08:52.574
Chuck it. Done.
Start over.

08:52.574 --> 08:56.202
<i>[tense music]</i>

08:56.202 --> 08:58.580
- We are almost one hour
into this first round

08:58.580 --> 09:00.206
of competition,

09:00.206 --> 09:02.083
and Mike is starting over.

09:02.083 --> 09:05.670
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:05.670 --> 09:07.630
<i>- I am hot.</i>
<i>I may have</i>

09:07.630 --> 09:09.507
breathed in some scale.
I'm not wearing a mask

09:09.507 --> 09:11.176
like I normally do.

09:11.176 --> 09:13.386
Just one big piece
of hot metal.

09:13.386 --> 09:15.472
- It'll be interesting to see
how he wraps it up.

09:15.472 --> 09:17.140
It just seems to me
he's gonna have a lot

09:17.140 --> 09:20.101
of extra material
hanging over past his 1095.

09:20.101 --> 09:22.645
<i>- This is taking a lot longer</i>
<i>than I thought it would.</i>

09:22.645 --> 09:25.106
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:25.106 --> 09:26.649
<i>- First half</i>
<i>of the challenge,</i>

09:26.649 --> 09:28.359
I felt I was moving
at a turtle's pace

09:28.359 --> 09:30.904
<i>because the size</i>
<i>and thickness of the steel</i>

09:30.904 --> 09:33.364
<i>that I'm working with</i>
<i>is much bigger</i>

09:33.364 --> 09:35.158
than what I'm used
to working with at home.

09:35.158 --> 09:36.242
Kind of took me
a little longer

09:36.242 --> 09:37.786
to get her
put together but...

09:37.786 --> 09:40.455
She's solid now, so!

09:40.455 --> 09:42.707
But once I got that steel
forge welded,

09:42.707 --> 09:44.250
I know I can make
a knife out of it.

09:44.250 --> 09:45.668
I'm gonna have to be heavy
on the grinder

09:45.668 --> 09:47.879
on this bad boy.

09:47.879 --> 09:51.049
- I enjoy making blades
because it's something

09:51.049 --> 09:52.801
that I can do
with my hands.

09:52.801 --> 09:54.844
<i>Pick up a piece of steel</i>
<i>and look at it,</i>

09:54.844 --> 09:57.931
and kind of think,
"What does this need to be?"

09:57.931 --> 09:59.933
<i>As I'm drawing</i>
<i>the tang out,</i>

09:59.933 --> 10:02.936
I start noticing
a little bit of delamination.

10:02.936 --> 10:05.355
- So I think Jim
might be chasing

10:05.355 --> 10:07.857
some delams and cracks
in his billet.

10:07.857 --> 10:09.150
- Yeah,
if he can grind those out,

10:09.150 --> 10:10.652
he can put that billet
back in the fire

10:10.652 --> 10:12.862
<i>and re-square it up again.</i>

10:12.862 --> 10:16.616
<i>[tense music]</i>

10:16.616 --> 10:18.910
- Oh, now we're doing
the hard part.

10:18.910 --> 10:20.745
Waiting for it to get up
to weld temp.

10:20.745 --> 10:22.497
- That sucks, man.

10:22.497 --> 10:24.457
<i>- Oh, man,</i>
<i>I'm way behind.</i>

10:24.457 --> 10:27.669
Seeing where they're at,
and mine's still in the fire,

10:27.669 --> 10:29.671
getting hot.
What can I do?

10:29.671 --> 10:31.256
Nothing.
Drink some water.

10:31.256 --> 10:33.925
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:33.925 --> 10:35.969
<i>- So I'm standing</i>
<i>at the forge.</i>

10:35.969 --> 10:38.304
<i>And that sense of,</i>

10:38.304 --> 10:40.723
"What's happening here?"

10:40.723 --> 10:42.976
I actually start
to feel pressure

10:42.976 --> 10:45.728
in my jaw,
in my left arm.

10:45.728 --> 10:48.273
<i>It just seems</i>
<i>to snowball on me.</i>

10:48.273 --> 10:49.732
<i>Time seemed</i>
<i>to kind of...</i>

10:49.732 --> 10:51.568
Get distorted for me.

10:51.568 --> 10:55.488
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:55.488 --> 10:57.490
- All right, hold on,
the medic's on the floor.

11:01.119 --> 11:02.704
- Is the world spinning on you?
- Yeah.

11:02.704 --> 11:04.497
- Perry's just locked up.

11:04.497 --> 11:07.000
- Let's go behind you.
- Man... Oh...

11:07.000 --> 11:08.720
- I have to go down.
- He's going down.

11:11.963 --> 11:14.132
- Whoa, whoa, whoa.
- Sit down. Sit down.

11:14.132 --> 11:15.842
Perry, sit up.

11:15.842 --> 11:17.802
- [groans]

11:17.802 --> 11:19.762
- I wanna get an ambulance,
I'll tell you why.

11:19.762 --> 11:22.098
You're on my rules now,
that's it.

11:22.098 --> 11:25.351
- Here, I'm saying,
"Get back on the floor."

11:25.351 --> 11:28.396
Here, I'm saying, "No."

11:28.396 --> 11:30.815
- Hey, if it's nothing,
you go and you'll be fine.

11:30.815 --> 11:32.358
If it's something,
they can at least

11:32.358 --> 11:34.068
correct the problem.

11:34.068 --> 11:35.361
All right?
- And at that moment,

11:35.361 --> 11:36.946
I realized,
"I'm gonna put my pride

11:36.946 --> 11:38.323
and my ego to the side."

11:38.323 --> 11:39.490
<i>Something's wrong.</i>

11:39.490 --> 11:41.409
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:41.409 --> 11:43.453
<i>- So we've got</i>
<i>the paramedics coming in</i>

11:43.453 --> 11:46.414
<i>to take Perry out of here.</i>

11:46.414 --> 11:48.917
Here's what you gotta
respect about Perry:

11:48.917 --> 11:52.253
he worked until
he couldn't stand anymore.

11:52.253 --> 11:53.671
And there's a lot
to be said

11:53.671 --> 11:55.381
for that kind of tenacity.

11:58.760 --> 12:00.637
<i>- I'm going home.</i>

12:00.637 --> 12:02.472
I just didn't want
to go out on a stretcher.

12:02.472 --> 12:04.557
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:04.557 --> 12:07.518
- I know that three of us
are not gonna win this.

12:07.518 --> 12:11.856
But I hate for Perry
to go out like he did.

12:11.856 --> 12:13.524
- Thirty minutes, bladesmiths!

12:13.524 --> 12:16.694
You have thirty minutes
remaining in this round!

12:16.694 --> 12:18.071
In case you didn't notice,

12:18.071 --> 12:19.322
Perry has been medical-dropped.

12:19.322 --> 12:21.032
But that's not a free pass!

12:21.032 --> 12:24.410
Your blades still need
to be up to par.

12:24.410 --> 12:26.246
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:26.246 --> 12:27.497
- Yeah,
Mike is back on track.

12:27.497 --> 12:29.123
That's good.
- Oh, yeah.

12:29.123 --> 12:31.167
<i>- I set my welds</i>
<i>on that second one,</i>

12:31.167 --> 12:32.961
<i>and everything</i>
<i>is phenomenal.</i>

12:32.961 --> 12:35.129
I am in my zone,
and I'm just

12:35.129 --> 12:36.673
letting the steel take me
on a beautiful trip.

12:36.673 --> 12:39.717
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:39.717 --> 12:41.552
<i>- Jim has quenched.</i>

12:41.552 --> 12:43.638
<i>- I pulled my blade</i>
<i>out of the quencher oil,</i>

12:43.638 --> 12:46.015
and my blade
has a warp in it.

12:46.015 --> 12:48.977
- Now he's got his blade
locked into the vice,

12:48.977 --> 12:51.437
and he's aggressively
trying to take

12:51.437 --> 12:53.690
a warp or a bend
out of it.

12:53.690 --> 12:55.733
- A little nerve-racking,
watching that.

12:55.733 --> 12:57.610
- This may look scary,

12:57.610 --> 12:59.904
but I'm confident
that I can straighten it out

12:59.904 --> 13:02.198
without it breaking.

13:02.198 --> 13:05.285
<i>[energetic music]</i>

13:05.285 --> 13:07.161
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:07.161 --> 13:09.622
<i>- Jon's in the quench.</i>

13:09.622 --> 13:12.625
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:12.625 --> 13:14.794
<i>- All of a sudden,</i>
<i>I'm noticing a warp,</i>

13:14.794 --> 13:16.337
<i>uh, at the tip.</i>

13:16.337 --> 13:17.797
If I can't get
to the point

13:17.797 --> 13:19.924
where it's
absolutely straight...

13:19.924 --> 13:21.634
Back to the grinder we go.

13:21.634 --> 13:23.386
Nothing I can do
at this point.

13:23.386 --> 13:25.263
- Thirty seconds!

13:25.263 --> 13:27.015
- Let's move!
Time to really make this go!

13:27.015 --> 13:29.392
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:29.392 --> 13:31.769
<i>I started over,</i>
<i>and I still caught up,</i>

13:31.769 --> 13:34.772
and showed what I'm worth.
- Ten! Nine!

13:34.772 --> 13:36.649
Eight! Seven!

13:36.649 --> 13:38.818
Six! Five!

13:38.818 --> 13:40.611
Four! Three!

13:40.611 --> 13:42.739
Two! One!

13:42.739 --> 13:44.365
Bladesmiths,
shut down your machines,

13:44.365 --> 13:45.867
drop your tools!

13:45.867 --> 13:47.744
This round is over!

13:47.744 --> 13:49.287
- Feeling pretty good.

13:49.287 --> 13:51.247
Had some hiccups there,

13:51.247 --> 13:53.416
but I overcame them
as best I could.

13:53.416 --> 13:55.126
<i>And I know</i>
<i>I've got a knife,</i>

13:55.126 --> 13:57.003
and I'm proud of it.

13:57.003 --> 13:59.547
- All right, gentlemen.
We asked you bladesmiths,

13:59.547 --> 14:03.092
who are also military veterans,
to forge a combat knife.

14:03.092 --> 14:05.678
Now, just because we've had
a medical drop

14:05.678 --> 14:08.222
doesn't mean that you all
get a free pass.

14:08.222 --> 14:10.391
You still have to fulfill
the mission parameters.

14:10.391 --> 14:12.101
Jon, you're up first.

14:12.101 --> 14:14.103
Please present your blade
to the judges.

14:14.103 --> 14:16.439
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:16.439 --> 14:18.524
<i>- The steel looks good.</i>
<i>Think the profile</i>

14:18.524 --> 14:20.068
<i>of your knife's</i>
<i>really good looking.</i>

14:20.068 --> 14:22.695
<i>For a stab in the chop,</i>
<i>having some mass</i>

14:22.695 --> 14:24.655
<i>behind that blade's</i>
<i>gonna help.</i>

14:24.655 --> 14:27.700
But, I'd love to see this
lose some weight.

14:27.700 --> 14:29.786
- Our only Marine.

14:29.786 --> 14:32.663
Mike, please present your blade
to the judges.

14:32.663 --> 14:34.874
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:34.874 --> 14:36.959
<i>- First up,</i>
<i>good job knowing</i>

14:36.959 --> 14:38.586
<i>when to start over.</i>

14:38.586 --> 14:41.881
This looks like
a very nice slashing weapon.

14:41.881 --> 14:43.800
Thrusting-wise,
with a trailing point

14:43.800 --> 14:45.718
over there,
you have to adjust.

14:45.718 --> 14:47.261
So, want to be able to have
a little bit more

14:47.261 --> 14:48.596
of an angle
that comes to a point

14:48.596 --> 14:51.140
to where,
I don't have to adjust.

14:51.140 --> 14:53.059
- All right, Jim.
You're up.

14:53.059 --> 14:54.852
Please present your blade
to the judges.

14:54.852 --> 14:56.646
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:56.646 --> 14:58.606
<i>- Classic spear point.</i>

14:58.606 --> 15:01.400
<i>Great cutting,</i>
<i>great thrusting design.</i>

15:01.400 --> 15:03.653
Big concern for me,

15:03.653 --> 15:06.405
is this seam
going right down the middle

15:06.405 --> 15:07.865
of the spine
of your knife.

15:07.865 --> 15:09.575
Okay?

15:09.575 --> 15:11.577
'Cause you don't want
anything opening up

15:11.577 --> 15:13.788
when they start
doing that strength test.

15:13.788 --> 15:16.499
But, uh,
I love the shape of it.

15:16.499 --> 15:18.334
Nice job.
- Thank you, sir.

15:18.334 --> 15:20.169
<i>Even with Perry out,</i>

15:20.169 --> 15:22.672
that doesn't necessarily mean
that we all go through

15:22.672 --> 15:23.881
<i>to the next phase.</i>

15:23.881 --> 15:25.800
<i>So I'm a little bit nervous.</i>

15:25.800 --> 15:27.718
- Okay, bladesmiths.

15:27.718 --> 15:29.262
The judges have completed
their deliberation,

15:29.262 --> 15:31.389
and they've made
a final decision.

15:31.389 --> 15:34.016
The judges agreed that you all
have passed parameters

15:34.016 --> 15:36.060
and you will be moving on
to round two.

15:36.060 --> 15:37.770
Congratulations.

15:37.770 --> 15:39.689
In this round,
you'll be attaching handles

15:39.689 --> 15:40.857
to your blades,
to turn them into

15:40.857 --> 15:42.817
fully-functional
combat knives.

15:42.817 --> 15:45.319
You'll have three hours
in which to do this.

15:45.319 --> 15:47.905
Use your time wisely.

15:47.905 --> 15:50.741
Because when the time runs out,
your blades will be tested

15:50.741 --> 15:52.410
for strength and durability

15:52.410 --> 15:54.495
in that ammo can strength test.

15:54.495 --> 15:57.540
And for sharpness,
in a resupply bundle slice.

15:57.540 --> 15:59.667
There is one addition:

15:59.667 --> 16:03.713
The combat knife isn't just
for slashing and stabbing.

16:03.713 --> 16:06.549
Sometimes, you gotta
smash and bash.

16:06.549 --> 16:08.843
So you'll need
to include a bolster,

16:08.843 --> 16:11.179
<i>or a butt cap,</i>
<i>as well as a guard</i>

16:11.179 --> 16:12.930
<i>to protect the hand.</i>

16:12.930 --> 16:15.766
Good luck.
Three hours starts... now.

16:15.766 --> 16:17.393
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:17.393 --> 16:19.645
- Yeah, baby!
I need to take

16:19.645 --> 16:21.606
the judges' critique
into account.

16:21.606 --> 16:23.941
And I know I need
to reshape my blade.

16:23.941 --> 16:26.611
- If you look
at Jon's blade,

16:26.611 --> 16:29.572
It's thick, it's heavy,
it's not combat ready.

16:29.572 --> 16:31.032
Would you guys agree?
- Yes.

16:31.032 --> 16:33.284
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:33.284 --> 16:34.952
- My strategy is
to get my handle

16:34.952 --> 16:36.621
banged out first,
and then go back

16:36.621 --> 16:39.165
to polish and sharpen.

16:39.165 --> 16:41.042
<i>I'm looking for</i>
<i>a nice hard wood.</i>

16:41.042 --> 16:43.628
And all I could find
was a piece of softer cherry.

16:43.628 --> 16:46.130
<i>Softer woods</i>
<i>tend to crack easier,</i>

16:46.130 --> 16:49.300
<i>so I'm a little concerned</i>
<i>with that.</i>

16:49.300 --> 16:51.594
- I think that maybe
Mike is gonna

16:51.594 --> 16:56.224
mortise his tang
into that material.

16:56.224 --> 16:58.517
- When I carve out the tang,
it has to be very accurate

16:58.517 --> 17:00.603
so that it sets nicely.

17:02.647 --> 17:04.607
- I have to do
a few things to this blade

17:04.607 --> 17:06.442
before I start
putting the handle on.

17:06.442 --> 17:09.153
But I'm not sure
that I'm gonna be able

17:09.153 --> 17:12.114
to grind all that delamination
out on the spine.

17:12.114 --> 17:14.033
But I've got another
little trick up my sleeve

17:14.033 --> 17:15.618
that I may show 'em later.

17:15.618 --> 17:17.328
- That is some
pretty aggressive grinding

17:17.328 --> 17:19.163
Jim's doing
with that thin blade.

17:19.163 --> 17:21.249
- Jim already took a lot
away from this blade

17:21.249 --> 17:23.125
for the first round,
and he's gotta be careful

17:23.125 --> 17:26.337
how much he takes away
from the spine of it.

17:26.337 --> 17:28.839
- Bladesmiths!
60 minutes has elapsed!

17:28.839 --> 17:30.675
- I'm happy with
where my blade is at,

17:30.675 --> 17:32.051
and now it's time
to get to this handle

17:32.051 --> 17:34.345
<i>and the guard.</i>

17:34.345 --> 17:36.013
I'm gonna split
the wood part of my handle

17:36.013 --> 17:38.641
into two pieces,
to add a little bit of comfort.

17:38.641 --> 17:40.226
<i>Knowing the parameters,</i>

17:40.226 --> 17:41.852
<i>I'm going to go</i>
<i>with a brass guard.</i>

17:41.852 --> 17:43.437
So it's gonna go brass,

17:43.437 --> 17:46.065
<i>leather, wood,</i>
<i>leather, wood,</i>

17:46.065 --> 17:48.901
little more leather,
and then my brass butt cap.

17:48.901 --> 17:50.653
- Jon definitely made sure
he didn't go

17:50.653 --> 17:52.238
on the lean side
with his handle material.

17:52.238 --> 17:55.491
He's got plenty there
to grind down.

17:55.491 --> 17:57.368
- That'll do, Donkey,
that'll do.

17:57.368 --> 18:00.496
<i>[energetic music]</i>

18:00.496 --> 18:02.540
- Damn it.
<i>I noticed I've got</i>

18:02.540 --> 18:04.083
<i>an 1/8 of an inch off</i>
<i>from my hand guard</i>

18:04.083 --> 18:06.127
<i>to my shoulders on my blade.</i>

18:06.127 --> 18:08.296
Now it's time to fix it,
and it's just

18:08.296 --> 18:11.048
throwing my timetable
completely off.

18:11.048 --> 18:13.009
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:13.009 --> 18:14.719
- Is he making
a little slotted shim,

18:14.719 --> 18:16.220
is that what he's doing?
- I think so, yeah.

18:16.220 --> 18:19.056
- Oh, oh.

18:19.056 --> 18:22.560
<i>[tense music]</i>

18:22.560 --> 18:24.478
- Son of a bitch...
- He cracked his handle--

18:24.478 --> 18:25.932
- Oh, God.
- Oh, my God!

18:27.732 --> 18:30.151
<i>- This handle</i>
<i>just cracked open.</i>

18:30.151 --> 18:32.111
<i>And my heart sinks.</i>

18:32.111 --> 18:34.905
- Round two,
starting over again.

18:34.905 --> 18:37.325
<i>- All right.</i>
<i>We're gonna glue it up,</i>

18:37.325 --> 18:39.076
<i>and we're gonna shim it up</i>
<i>with leather around it</i>

18:39.076 --> 18:40.661
<i>so that it gets</i>
<i>stiff and hard.</i>

18:40.661 --> 18:42.913
And then we'll
make that spacer.

18:42.913 --> 18:46.292
Everything will go fine,
and we'll just move on.

18:46.292 --> 18:48.419
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:48.419 --> 18:50.463
<i>[lighthearted music]</i>

18:50.463 --> 18:53.007
- [laughs]
Jim.

18:53.007 --> 18:54.467
- I can't find my knife!

18:54.467 --> 18:57.136
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:57.136 --> 18:59.305
I'm sure I had it over here.
- Oh, he's got the drops!

18:59.305 --> 19:01.098
[all laughing]

19:01.098 --> 19:02.933
- This is nothing new,
I do this in my shop

19:02.933 --> 19:04.810
all the time.

19:04.810 --> 19:06.395
Right there!

19:06.395 --> 19:08.481
- Shop gremlins, man,
shop gremlins!

19:08.481 --> 19:10.399
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:10.399 --> 19:12.485
- After the epoxy sets,
I know I've gotta start shaping

19:12.485 --> 19:13.903
<i>this big block</i>
<i>of wood and leather.</i>

19:13.903 --> 19:15.363
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:15.363 --> 19:16.906
<i>So as I'm grinding,</i>

19:16.906 --> 19:18.032
I notice my guard
is pretty loose,

19:18.032 --> 19:19.659
it's got a wiggle.

19:19.659 --> 19:21.327
Oh, that's not good.
I don't have time

19:21.327 --> 19:23.954
to rework this handle.
Gotta fix this, quick.

19:23.954 --> 19:25.956
- So Jon's mixing up
epoxy right now,

19:25.956 --> 19:27.708
<i>what is he doing,</i>
<i>is he gap-filling?</i>

19:27.708 --> 19:29.835
<i>- Yeah, he's gap-filling.</i>

19:29.835 --> 19:31.087
- Just kind of hold it there
with my hands

19:31.087 --> 19:32.296
and compress it,
pray to the blade gods

19:32.296 --> 19:33.422
<i>that it holds.</i>

19:33.422 --> 19:35.257
I'm imparting my spirit

19:35.257 --> 19:37.134
into the guard.

19:37.134 --> 19:38.969
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:38.969 --> 19:40.763
- Handle's repaired,
it's like, "All right,

19:40.763 --> 19:44.725
let's get this polished up
and sharpened."

19:44.725 --> 19:46.310
She ain't the sexiest girl
at the ball,

19:46.310 --> 19:48.479
but I'll tell you what,
she's gonna dance better

19:48.479 --> 19:49.522
than anybody else.

19:50.981 --> 19:53.401
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:53.401 --> 19:55.403
<i>- I've got my blade</i>
<i>about where I want to.</i>

19:55.403 --> 19:57.029
Everything is looking good.

19:57.029 --> 19:58.989
- He had the reverse grip,
I haven't seen

19:58.989 --> 20:00.700
the reverse grip stab yet.

20:00.700 --> 20:03.327
That guy probably knows
what he's doing.

20:03.327 --> 20:07.415
- I think I've still got time
to do my special trick.

20:07.415 --> 20:09.166
If all the judges
aren't saying,

20:09.166 --> 20:11.210
"What is he doing right now?"

20:11.210 --> 20:13.796
- You only have
one minute remaining!

20:13.796 --> 20:15.256
What are you doing, Jim?

20:15.256 --> 20:17.425
Start doing my
down-and-dirty

20:17.425 --> 20:19.176
"fast firework."

20:19.176 --> 20:21.220
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:21.220 --> 20:23.639
- He's grinding saw teeth
into the spine of that blade!

20:23.639 --> 20:26.767
If that's not a multi-purpose
combat blade,

20:26.767 --> 20:28.686
I don't know what is.

20:28.686 --> 20:30.354
[laughing]

20:30.354 --> 20:32.356
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:32.356 --> 20:34.108
<i>- He's just trying</i>
<i>to camouflage that seam</i>

20:34.108 --> 20:36.235
<i>going right down the middle</i>
<i>of the spine.</i>

20:36.235 --> 20:38.362
<i>- I can still see it.</i>
<i>- But good attempt, though.</i>

20:38.362 --> 20:40.448
- My special trick covered up
what may have been

20:40.448 --> 20:43.117
some small imperfections
still in the spine.

20:43.117 --> 20:44.243
<i>You can't see them now.</i>

20:44.243 --> 20:45.536
- Five!

20:45.536 --> 20:46.662
Four!

20:46.662 --> 20:47.913
Three!

20:47.913 --> 20:49.832
Two!
One!

20:49.832 --> 20:51.751
Bladesmiths,
drop your tools!

20:51.751 --> 20:53.419
Shut down your machines!

20:53.419 --> 20:56.964
This round of competition
is over!

20:56.964 --> 20:59.341
- I think my blade is gonna
do real well.

20:59.341 --> 21:01.010
<i>Kind of worried</i>
<i>about the thrust,</i>

21:01.010 --> 21:02.803
a little bit.
Like that hand guard,

21:02.803 --> 21:06.223
<i>just got a shim</i>
<i>holding it in place nicely.</i>

21:06.223 --> 21:07.600
- All right, smiths.

21:07.600 --> 21:09.477
Welcome to
our strength test:

21:09.477 --> 21:11.604
<i>The ammo can</i>
<i>stab and chop.</i>

21:11.604 --> 21:13.773
What will your blades
do to the cans?

21:13.773 --> 21:15.775
I don't really care.
I want to see what the cans

21:15.775 --> 21:17.151
are gonna do
to your blades.

21:17.151 --> 21:18.486
Jon, I know you're ready
for this, right?

21:18.486 --> 21:21.197
- Rock and roll.
- Let's do it.

21:21.197 --> 21:22.782
<i>- My heart is going</i>
<i>a thousand miles an hour</i>

21:22.782 --> 21:24.450
<i>right now.</i>
<i>The only thing</i>

21:24.450 --> 21:26.327
<i>I'm really worried about</i>
<i>is that guard.</i>

21:26.327 --> 21:28.329
<i>I didn't get it solid,</i>
<i>to fit up as I wanted to.</i>

21:28.329 --> 21:30.331
That guard is
a little bit sloppy.

21:30.331 --> 21:32.958
<i>[tense music]</i>

21:32.958 --> 21:34.502
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:34.502 --> 21:37.588
Yeah, boy.
- [grunts]

21:37.588 --> 21:40.591
<i>[exciting music]</i>

21:40.591 --> 21:45.471
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:47.556 --> 21:50.309
<i>[tense music]</i>

21:50.309 --> 21:52.478
- Jon, it's a beast.

21:52.478 --> 21:54.897
But it's actually
a fairly comfortable beast.

21:54.897 --> 21:58.192
The leather behind the guard...

21:58.192 --> 22:00.694
I mean, it's still there,
but it makes it move a bit.

22:00.694 --> 22:03.906
But, there's no cracking.

22:03.906 --> 22:06.075
There's no huge chunks
taken out of it.

22:06.075 --> 22:08.118
Everything's tight.

22:08.118 --> 22:10.037
Nicely done.
- Thank you.

22:10.037 --> 22:11.413
- All right, Mike,

22:11.413 --> 22:12.623
what's the Marine Corps
got to say?

22:12.623 --> 22:13.791
- Let's do this.
- Let's do it.

22:13.791 --> 22:15.918
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:15.918 --> 22:17.545
<i>I am very nervous.</i>

22:17.545 --> 22:19.088
Jon just went,
his blade

22:19.088 --> 22:20.881
dented that can up
really nice.

22:20.881 --> 22:22.508
My turn.
Let's do this.

22:22.508 --> 22:24.969
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:24.969 --> 22:27.304
- [grunts]

22:27.304 --> 22:33.853
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:39.567 --> 22:41.068
- Yeah, boy.

22:41.068 --> 22:42.778
- All right, Mike,
some handle things.

22:42.778 --> 22:44.280
It's a very large handle.

22:44.280 --> 22:46.282
That being said,
with this big chunk

22:46.282 --> 22:48.033
of brass on the back,
I was able to generate

22:48.033 --> 22:49.910
a lot of force
in that stab.

22:49.910 --> 22:52.037
The only problem is,
we did take

22:52.037 --> 22:54.665
a bit of your tip off,
in the stab.

22:54.665 --> 22:56.000
Except for
a few little chips,

22:56.000 --> 22:57.293
and a snapped tip,

22:57.293 --> 22:58.794
you've still got
a good edge, there.

22:58.794 --> 23:00.337
Good job.
- Thank you.

23:02.590 --> 23:03.924
- You can breathe.
- I can breathe.

23:03.924 --> 23:05.885
- You can breathe now, yeah.

23:05.885 --> 23:09.054
Jim, I know you're ready.
- Always.

23:09.054 --> 23:11.432
<i>I'm feeling pretty good</i>
<i>about going in to testing.</i>

23:11.432 --> 23:13.225
<i>My blade's</i>
<i>something the size</i>

23:13.225 --> 23:14.894
<i>that I would have used</i>
<i>in Vietnam.</i>

23:16.645 --> 23:18.522
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:18.522 --> 23:20.024
- [grunting]

23:20.024 --> 23:25.571
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:25.571 --> 23:27.323
- Nice.

23:27.323 --> 23:33.412
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:36.707 --> 23:37.958
- Well,

23:37.958 --> 23:40.294
we've got
a couple issues, Jim.

23:40.294 --> 23:42.171
The big issue
is your edge, here.

23:42.171 --> 23:44.131
On those three chops?

23:44.131 --> 23:46.467
The can kind of won
on that one.

23:46.467 --> 23:50.846
I think your edge got too thin
when you were grinding.

23:50.846 --> 23:53.057
But otherwise,

23:53.057 --> 23:54.892
it's all tight,
nothing blew apart.

23:54.892 --> 23:56.810
Nicely done.
- Thank you.

23:56.810 --> 23:58.187
- Good job.

23:58.187 --> 24:00.064
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:00.064 --> 24:02.483
- Bladesmiths,
this is the sharpness test.

24:02.483 --> 24:05.069
The resupply bundle slice.

24:05.069 --> 24:07.571
Now, in World War II,
we used to resupply our troops

24:07.571 --> 24:10.240
by dropping down these supplies
by parachute.

24:10.240 --> 24:12.743
And some would get hung up
on trees or branches.

24:12.743 --> 24:15.746
Well, to help me
liberate these supplies,

24:15.746 --> 24:17.456
I'll take your weapon,
see how sharp it is,

24:17.456 --> 24:19.541
to help me cut these cords.

24:19.541 --> 24:20.960
Jon, you're up first.
You ready?

24:20.960 --> 24:23.295
- Let's do it.
- Let's do this.

24:23.295 --> 24:25.965
<i>[tense music]</i>

24:25.965 --> 24:32.346
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:37.309 --> 24:40.562
<i>[energizing music]</i>

24:40.562 --> 24:45.275
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:46.610 --> 24:48.988
- Nice.

24:48.988 --> 24:50.155
- All right, Jon.

24:50.155 --> 24:51.949
It's a big blade.

24:51.949 --> 24:54.618
But it's evenly balanced
all the way through.

24:54.618 --> 24:56.161
When you swing,
you can almost feel

24:56.161 --> 24:58.038
the power behind the blade.

24:58.038 --> 25:01.792
Overall, it will cut.
- Thank you, sir.

25:01.792 --> 25:04.211
That's what I wanted to hear.

25:04.211 --> 25:06.005
- All right, Mike,
you ready?

25:06.005 --> 25:08.382
- Let's make this happen.
- Let's do this.

25:08.382 --> 25:11.510
<i>[militaristic music]</i>

25:11.510 --> 25:16.390
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:16.390 --> 25:18.976
<i>[victorious music]</i>

25:18.976 --> 25:20.602
- Nice.

25:20.602 --> 25:26.233
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:28.819 --> 25:30.612
- Nice.
- Good job.

25:30.612 --> 25:32.489
- Mike, let's talk
about your blade.

25:32.489 --> 25:33.907
First up,
I love the balance.

25:33.907 --> 25:35.325
It feels good.

25:35.325 --> 25:38.454
And as you can see,
it cut easily.

25:38.454 --> 25:39.788
It will cut.

25:39.788 --> 25:42.291
- Thank you.
- Good job.

25:42.291 --> 25:43.459
- All right, Jim,
your turn.

25:43.459 --> 25:45.586
You ready?
- Let's do this.

25:45.586 --> 25:47.421
<i>During the ammo can chop,</i>

25:47.421 --> 25:50.966
I lost several pieces
of the blade.

25:50.966 --> 25:53.078
<i>I'm really hoping</i>
<i>at least I can cut something.</i>

25:53.510 --> 25:54.562
[grunts]

25:59.266 --> 26:02.269
<i>[tense music]</i>

26:02.269 --> 26:06.106
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:06.106 --> 26:07.566
This is not good.

26:07.566 --> 26:09.735
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:11.987 --> 26:17.451
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:20.913 --> 26:22.706
- All right, Jim,
let's talk about your blade.

26:22.706 --> 26:24.249
The handle itself feels good.

26:24.249 --> 26:26.543
Of all the blades,
this is very light.

26:26.543 --> 26:27.961
In the swing,
it feels good,

26:27.961 --> 26:29.505
it's got a good balance to it.

26:29.505 --> 26:30.964
But you are missing chips

26:30.964 --> 26:32.549
right there,
off the metal right there.

26:32.549 --> 26:35.886
It is just not sharp enough
to cut through the cord.

26:35.886 --> 26:38.597
- I understand.

26:38.597 --> 26:41.058
- Bladesmiths,
the judges have made

26:41.058 --> 26:42.893
their final decision,
and it's time for one of you

26:42.893 --> 26:44.520
to leave the forge.

26:44.520 --> 26:47.231
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:47.231 --> 26:48.690
Jim.

26:48.690 --> 26:50.234
Your blade did not
make the cut.

26:50.234 --> 26:51.568
- Jim, first of all,

26:51.568 --> 26:53.737
I want to thank you
for your service.

26:53.737 --> 26:55.155
And it was a pleasure
to watch you

26:55.155 --> 26:56.824
forge that knife
and finish it off.

26:56.824 --> 26:58.575
<i>But, during</i>
<i>that strength test,</i>

26:58.575 --> 27:00.285
<i>your blade</i>
<i>got beat up pretty bad.</i>

27:00.285 --> 27:02.246
<i>And couldn't perform</i>
<i>in the sharpness test.</i>

27:02.246 --> 27:03.789
And that's why
we're letting you go.

27:03.789 --> 27:05.457
- I understand.

27:05.457 --> 27:07.209
- Jim, I'd never ask you
to surrender your weapon.

27:07.209 --> 27:10.754
But I do have to ask you
to please turn it in.

27:10.754 --> 27:12.798
<i>- I came here to prove</i>
<i>that I could compete</i>

27:12.798 --> 27:14.925
with other smiths,
and I did that.

27:14.925 --> 27:16.343
[indistinct chatter]

27:16.343 --> 27:18.887
I may not be
a "Forged in Fire" Champion,

27:18.887 --> 27:21.223
<i>but I think</i>
<i>for a 70-year-old,</i>

27:21.223 --> 27:22.432
I did pretty well.

27:22.432 --> 27:25.769
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:25.769 --> 27:28.146
- Jon, Mike,
congratulations.

27:28.146 --> 27:29.690
When you showed up here,
we asked you

27:29.690 --> 27:31.441
to make combat knives.

27:31.441 --> 27:33.026
Now we're sending you back
to your home forges

27:33.026 --> 27:36.154
to recreate
an iconic weapon from history.

27:36.154 --> 27:37.656
That weapon is...

27:37.656 --> 27:40.242
<i>[cymbal shimmering]</i>

27:40.242 --> 27:44.037
The U. S. M1917 Naval cutlass.

27:44.037 --> 27:45.914
- All right.

27:45.914 --> 27:48.792
<i>- Produced by the U. S. Navy,</i>
<i>the M1917 cutlass</i>

27:48.792 --> 27:51.795
<i>is the American descendant</i>
<i>of earlier seafaring weapons,</i>

27:51.795 --> 27:54.631
<i>favored by British sailors</i>
<i>and Caribbean pirates.</i>

27:54.631 --> 27:56.550
<i>Based on</i>
<i>a Dutch Army cutlass,</i>

27:56.550 --> 27:58.927
<i>the sword features</i>
<i>a large, bow-like steel guard,</i>

27:58.927 --> 28:00.804
<i>and a wooden grip</i>
<i>secured by copper rivets</i>

28:00.804 --> 28:02.639
<i>that help defend</i>
<i>the user's hand.</i>

28:02.639 --> 28:04.975
<i>Fitted with over 2 feet</i>
<i>of curved blade,</i>

28:04.975 --> 28:06.977
<i>it was ideal for both</i>
<i>cutting and thrusting.</i>

28:06.977 --> 28:09.396
<i>Primarily being used</i>
<i>to slice through rope,</i>

28:09.396 --> 28:11.148
<i>canvas,</i>
<i>and, more brutally,</i>

28:11.148 --> 28:12.399
<i>flesh and bone.</i>

28:12.399 --> 28:14.484
<i>Successors of the M1917</i>

28:14.484 --> 28:16.486
<i>accompanied U. S. Marines</i>
<i>into combat</i>

28:16.486 --> 28:18.530
<i>in World War II's</i>
<i>Pacific theater.</i>

28:18.530 --> 28:20.824
<i>And today, it lives on</i>
<i>in modern video games</i>

28:20.824 --> 28:23.368
<i>such as "Battlefield 1,"</i>
<i>where players can wield it</i>

28:23.368 --> 28:24.745
<i>in melee combat.</i>

28:24.745 --> 28:26.788
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:26.788 --> 28:29.041
<i>It must have fullers</i>
<i>on both sides of the blade,</i>

28:29.041 --> 28:30.792
<i>and a right-handed</i>
<i>bell guard.</i>

28:30.792 --> 28:32.252
- Now, I'm an Army guy.

28:32.252 --> 28:33.837
We don't carry Navy swords.

28:33.837 --> 28:36.214
<i>I think the Marines do,</i>
<i>so I think Mike,</i>

28:36.214 --> 28:38.050
<i>he's got a little one-up</i>
<i>on me right now.</i>

28:38.050 --> 28:39.843
- You will have five days
at your home forges

28:39.843 --> 28:41.553
to complete this challenge.

28:41.553 --> 28:44.181
Now, I want you guys
to really think about

28:44.181 --> 28:47.643
what you're trying
to commemorate here.

28:47.643 --> 28:51.480
Take all of that energy,
and put it into this blade.

28:51.480 --> 28:53.941
Good luck.
We'll see you in five days.

28:53.941 --> 28:55.275
- All right.
- Good luck, man.

28:55.275 --> 28:56.652
- You're gonna need it, man.

28:56.652 --> 28:58.236
- Jon, Mike said
you're gonna need it.

28:58.236 --> 28:59.947
You better represent.

28:59.947 --> 29:02.324
- Marines are always full
of hot air.

29:02.324 --> 29:05.369
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:05.369 --> 29:06.620
<i>- I live right under</i>
<i>the flight line</i>

29:06.620 --> 29:07.955
<i>for the Naval base.</i>

29:10.791 --> 29:12.584
<i>I do a little bit of a lot</i>
<i>of different style blades,</i>

29:12.584 --> 29:14.419
<i>from spears to axes,</i>

29:14.419 --> 29:16.463
so this cutlass
shouldn't be a problem.

29:16.463 --> 29:18.090
<i>But, never know</i>
<i>when something's</i>

29:18.090 --> 29:20.008
<i>gonna go sideways.</i>

29:20.008 --> 29:21.969
<i>Today I plan on</i>
<i>having my blade done</i>

29:21.969 --> 29:23.470
and tempered.

29:23.470 --> 29:25.514
My mentor,
when he was younger--

29:25.514 --> 29:26.974
<i>If you couldn't make</i>
<i>a basic knife,</i>

29:26.974 --> 29:28.475
<i>and have it</i>
<i>forged to shape</i>

29:28.475 --> 29:30.352
<i>and ready</i>
<i>for heat treating temp</i>

29:30.352 --> 29:33.021
<i>in three hours,</i>
<i>he threw you out of the shop.</i>

29:33.021 --> 29:35.732
And that's why I move so fast
when I'm working.

29:35.732 --> 29:38.652
I'm gonna quench.

29:38.652 --> 29:40.112
<i>Just went in the oil.</i>

29:40.112 --> 29:41.947
<i>It's nice, quiet.</i>

29:41.947 --> 29:43.448
<i>Just cooled.</i>

29:43.448 --> 29:45.450
<i>No pops, no "tings."</i>

29:45.450 --> 29:47.744
Sigh of relief.

29:47.744 --> 29:48.996
[grunts]

29:48.996 --> 29:50.789
And she is straight!

29:50.789 --> 29:53.417
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:53.417 --> 29:54.626
<i>- It feels really good</i>
<i>to be back</i>

29:54.626 --> 29:56.378
<i>in the home forge.</i>

29:56.378 --> 29:57.713
What I'd like
to get accomplished today

29:57.713 --> 29:59.798
is get my handle material
clamped up,

29:59.798 --> 30:01.216
<i>and ready to go.</i>

30:01.216 --> 30:02.926
And then also get
a rough-forge shape

30:02.926 --> 30:05.012
on my blade.

30:05.012 --> 30:07.180
<i>My handle will be</i>
<i>a canvas Micarta,</i>

30:07.180 --> 30:09.850
<i>gonna use khaki</i>
<i>and ODI green.</i>

30:09.850 --> 30:11.810
<i>Kind of an homage</i>
<i>to the uniforms</i>

30:11.810 --> 30:13.603
<i>that were worn on D-Day.</i>

30:13.603 --> 30:15.564
I'm taking my time,

30:15.564 --> 30:17.065
<i>making sure</i>
<i>everything's perfect</i>

30:17.065 --> 30:18.525
<i>before I move on</i>
<i>to the next step.</i>

30:18.525 --> 30:21.778
A little wiggle, there...

30:21.778 --> 30:24.740
<i>Just tweaking this blade,</i>
<i>and getting the length</i>

30:24.740 --> 30:27.325
and the thickness
that I really want.

30:27.325 --> 30:29.286
Uh, gotta go.

30:29.286 --> 30:30.537
You know, day one,
I really wanted

30:30.537 --> 30:32.205
to start forging out my tang.

30:32.205 --> 30:33.623
<i>And it's</i>
<i>a constant struggle of--</i>

30:33.623 --> 30:35.959
<i>and I just didn't</i>
<i>get there today.</i>

30:35.959 --> 30:38.462
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:38.462 --> 30:40.088
<i>- I'm feeling pretty confident</i>
<i>about all the stuff</i>

30:40.088 --> 30:41.757
<i>I got done yesterday.</i>

30:41.757 --> 30:43.633
Ideally,
what I'm looking at today

30:43.633 --> 30:45.677
is having everything done.

30:45.677 --> 30:48.513
<i>I'm in process of hammering</i>
<i>the bell guard out.</i>

30:48.513 --> 30:51.099
<i>Now we're gonna make it</i>
<i>a live blade.</i>

30:51.099 --> 30:52.476
<i>It's really easy,</i>
<i>when you're trying</i>

30:52.476 --> 30:53.935
<i>to polish</i>
<i>a little nick out,</i>

30:53.935 --> 30:56.271
to overheat it,
and blow your temper.

30:56.271 --> 30:58.398
<i>Gonna go out</i>
<i>and do the cut test.</i>

30:58.398 --> 30:59.900
This is the moment of truth.

30:59.900 --> 31:02.652
If it breaks,
we start all over.

31:02.652 --> 31:04.279
Hopefully everything
goes well,

31:04.279 --> 31:05.405
and I don't have
to make a new blade.

31:08.450 --> 31:10.243
<i>- This is the moment of truth.</i>

31:10.243 --> 31:13.371
<i>[tense music]</i>

31:13.371 --> 31:15.248
That'll do.
No marks.

31:15.248 --> 31:17.959
I don't think I need
to go any further.

31:17.959 --> 31:20.754
<i>Right now,</i>
<i>gonna do some brass casting.</i>

31:20.754 --> 31:24.132
<i>Creating the nautical star,</i>
<i>that was originally worn</i>

31:24.132 --> 31:26.093
<i>by sailors as good luck.</i>

31:26.093 --> 31:29.721
<i>I'm gonna make the star</i>
<i>the actual pommel nut.</i>

31:29.721 --> 31:31.765
<i>It will hold</i>
<i>the entire system together.</i>

31:31.765 --> 31:33.350
She's gonna be a beast.

31:33.350 --> 31:35.352
<i>I'm gonna start doing</i>
<i>a little bit</i>

31:35.352 --> 31:37.229
<i>of light engraving,</i>
<i>get the military's branches</i>

31:37.229 --> 31:39.397
<i>on the bell guard,</i>
<i>and their date of inception.</i>

31:39.397 --> 31:41.608
So, 16 hours,
the blade's done,

31:41.608 --> 31:45.862
scabbard's done, I'm done!

31:45.862 --> 31:47.364
<i>- Yesterday,</i>
<i>things weren't moving along</i>

31:47.364 --> 31:49.533
quite as expected.
So today,

31:49.533 --> 31:52.202
my biggest objective
is to get to the heat treat,

31:52.202 --> 31:54.454
<i>and the quench</i>
<i>halfway through the day.</i>

31:54.454 --> 31:56.915
<i>Now I need to finish</i>
<i>the fullers.</i>

31:56.915 --> 31:58.583
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:58.583 --> 32:00.335
Getting a really good result.

32:00.335 --> 32:02.212
So, very happy!

32:02.212 --> 32:03.630
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:03.630 --> 32:05.423
When in doubt,
more propane.

32:05.423 --> 32:08.260
<i>[tense music]</i>

32:08.260 --> 32:11.930
<i>If I don't nail this quench...</i>

32:11.930 --> 32:13.932
my piece is going
to be useless.

32:13.932 --> 32:17.185
We get it?
Did we get a straight blade?

32:17.185 --> 32:20.647
I think we did, by Jove!

32:20.647 --> 32:22.482
We got a good hardness, folks.

32:22.482 --> 32:24.776
Without the use
of pills, either.

32:24.776 --> 32:26.820
[laughs]
Yeah!

32:29.489 --> 32:31.950
<i>- It's day three,</i>
<i>blade's finished.</i>

32:31.950 --> 32:33.451
<i>I'm gonna relax</i>
<i>a little bit</i>

32:33.451 --> 32:35.871
and play with the animals.

32:35.871 --> 32:37.789
You want the Frisbee--
I see that look!

32:37.789 --> 32:39.207
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:39.207 --> 32:41.168
<i>I love you, Jon,</i>
<i>but...</i>

32:41.168 --> 32:44.504
I'm gonna kick your ass.

32:44.504 --> 32:46.882
<i>- I'm starting today</i>
<i>with the pommel.</i>

32:46.882 --> 32:48.592
<i>This serves</i>
<i>as a little bit</i>

32:48.592 --> 32:50.594
<i>of a counter-balance,</i>
<i>to the blade.</i>

32:50.594 --> 32:52.429
But it can also be used
to crack skulls.

32:52.429 --> 32:54.431
<i>My next step is</i>
<i>to blue the blade.</i>

32:54.431 --> 32:56.099
<i>Gives it a little</i>
<i>smoked glass,</i>

32:56.099 --> 32:58.310
<i>fog kind of look.</i>

32:58.310 --> 33:00.562
<i>It's kind of like</i>
<i>the final countdown here.</i>

33:00.562 --> 33:02.606
Nervous?
Hell yeah, I'm nervous.

33:02.606 --> 33:04.232
<i>You know,</i>
<i>after I send this blade out,</i>

33:04.232 --> 33:05.692
<i>I can't--</i>
<i>I can't tweak anything,</i>

33:05.692 --> 33:07.569
so it better be
ready to go.

33:07.569 --> 33:09.738
I'm happy with
my sharpness level,

33:09.738 --> 33:11.239
and I'm just gonna strop it

33:11.239 --> 33:13.158
